<p><strong>Internal linking after publishing:</strong> Every new article should link to 3-5 existing pages, and 3-5 existing pages should link back to the new article. This creates the cluster structure that builds <a href="/glossary/topical-authority/">topical authority</a>. Read our <a href="/blog/internal-linking-blog-posts/">internal linking guide</a> for the full strategy.</p>
<p><strong>Why this step matters:</strong> <a href="https://blog.hubspot.com/marketing/blogging-frequency-benchmarks">HubSpot research shows</a> that businesses publishing 16+ articles per month get 3.5x more organic traffic than those publishing 0-4. Consistency matters more than perfection. A gap analysis that produces 4 published articles per month will outperform a perfect analysis that sits in a spreadsheet.</p>
<p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Track results at 30, 60, and 90 days after publishing. Use Google Search Console to monitor impressions and position for each new page. If a page does not gain traction by day 90, revisit the search intent and competitor positioning. The SERP may have shifted since your analysis.</p>
